fields.name: Common Octopus
fields.description: Known for its intelligence and ability to camouflage, this octopus has a wide distribution in tropical and temperate seas around the world.

fields.name: Giant Pacific Octopus
fields.description: The largest species of octopus, it can weigh more than 600 pounds and measure over 30 feet across. Found in the North Pacific from Japan to California.

fields.name: Blue-Ringed Octopus
fields.description: Small but deadly, it's known for its bright blue rings that appear when threatened. The venom is potent enough to be fatal to humans.

fields.name: Mimic Octopus
fields.description: Famous for its ability to mimic other sea animals like flatfish, lionfish, and sea snakes to avoid predators. Found in Southeast Asia.

fields.name: Dumbo Octopus
fields.description: Named for its ear-like fins resembling the Disney character Dumbo. These deep-sea octopuses are found worldwide, typically in deep, cold ocean waters.

fields.name: Vampire Squid
fields.description: Despite its name, itâ€™s more closely related to octopuses than squids. Lives in extreme deep ocean environments and can emit bioluminescent clouds.

fields.name: California Two-Spot Octopus
fields.description: Easily identified by the two blue spots on either side of its head. Found in the Eastern Pacific, along the coast of California and Mexico.

fields.name: Coconut Octopus
fields.description: Known for using coconut shells and seashells as tools for protection and shelter. Found in the western Pacific Ocean.

fields.name: Atlantic Pygmy Octopus
fields.description: A small species that can fit in the palm of a hand, known for its curiosity and ability to escape from enclosures. Found in the Caribbean and along the Atlantic coast of the U.S.

fields.name: Wunderpus Photogenicus
fields.description: Distinguished by its striking pattern of white spots and bands on a reddish-brown body. Known for its dramatic display when threatened. Found in the waters of the Indo-Pacific.

fields.name: Striped Pyjama Octopus
fields.description: Actually a species of cuttlefish. Known for its distinctive stripes that resemble pajamas, this small octopus is found in shallow waters across the Indo-Pacific region.

fields.name: Red Octopus
fields.description: A small to medium-sized species known for its reddish-pink color, common along the Pacific coast of the United States.

fields.name: East Pacific Red Octopus
fields.description: Similar in appearance to the common red octopus but found specifically in the East Pacific region, noted for its intelligence and adaptability.

fields.name: Maori Octopus
fields.description: The largest octopus in New Zealand waters, known for its considerable size and strength, found in cooler southern Pacific waters.

fields.name: Ornate Octopus
fields.description: Features distinctive ornate patterns on its body, found in tropical waters of the western Pacific Ocean.

fields.name: Larger Pacific Striped Octopus
fields.description: Notable for its unique social behavior and striking striped appearance, found in the tropical eastern Pacific Ocean.

fields.name: Southern Sand Octopus
fields.description: Known for burrowing into the sand to hide from predators, this species is found along the southern coast of Australia.

fields.name: Atlantic White-spotted Octopus
fields.description: Characterized by its white spots and large size, this species is found in the Atlantic Ocean, particularly around the Iberian Peninsula.

fields.name: Night Octopus
fields.description: Active primarily at night, this octopus is found in the Indian and Pacific Oceans, known for its dark coloration and nocturnal hunting habits.

fields.name: Mosaic Octopus
fields.description: Small in size, this species is known for its mosaic-like patterns on its skin, found in the Indo-Pacific region.
